00:06:40.289 --> 00:06:46.870
If you're skeptical of the existence of this
third drive -- what are you doing here?

00:06:46.870 --> 00:06:51.960
No, I mean that. What are you doing here?
Here in this hour that we're going to spend

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:57.099
here at this little session?
It's a very, very attractive audience, full

00:06:57.099 --> 00:07:02.389
of attractive people, but my guess is that
in the next 45 minutes, no one is going to

00:07:02.389 --> 00:07:04.900
find a mate, okay?
So it's probably not going to answer your

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:10.979
biological urges being here.
Second, except for Martin, no one's making

00:07:10.979 --> 00:07:15.219
a buck here in the next hour, right?
So why are you here?

00:07:15.219 --> 00:07:17.159
You're here because you're curious.
You're here because you want to learn.

00:07:17.159 --> 00:07:20.120
You're here because you're part of a community.
You're here because you're going to engage.

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:23.430
That third drive is fundamental to what it
is to be a human being.

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:28.300
The trouble is -- and I think that you should
be grateful -- I mean, I think that you should

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:31.610
be grateful working here.
The trouble is that, in many businesses -- Google

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:37.511
being the exception in many ways -- many businesses
treat human beings as if that third drive

00:07:37.511 --> 00:07:40.169
doesn't exist, and that the second drive is
what it's all about.

00:07:40.169 --> 00:07:45.029
So that the way that they architect the systems
in their company -- the way they architect

00:07:45.029 --> 00:07:49.210
the compensation schemes -- the way they architect
their human resources policies -- is really

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:53.900
built around carrots and sticks, around "if-then"
rewards, "if you do this, then you get that."

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:58.680
And here's the thing -- and for this book,
I looked at -- and I'm grateful to Ilana for

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:02.400
mentioning that a lot of the books that I
write are very much grounded in the science.

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:06.850
I looked at 40 years of research -- 50 years
of research in the field of behavioral science

00:08:06.850 --> 00:08:11.589
 -- huge numbers of experiments by economists,
by sociologists, by psychologists about what

00:08:11.589 --> 00:08:14.780
really motivates us.
And what is clear from this 40 or 50 years

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:19.180
of research is that those "carrot and stick"
motivators -- those "if-then" motivators -- "if

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:23.680
you do this, then you do that" -- they work.
They work really, really well.

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:29.409
But they only work in a surprisingly narrow
band of circumstances -- a surprisingly narrow

00:08:29.409 --> 00:08:32.339
band of circumstances.
And that -- for many things that we do, and

00:08:32.339 --> 00:08:37.020
much of the work that you do here -- those
kinds of motivators -- those "if-then" motivators

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:41.090
 -- don't work.
In fact, they often do harm.

00:08:41.090 --> 00:08:47.110
So let me try to lay out some of this case
to you, because the research on this is absolutely

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:50.250
fascinating.
And so much of the research on human motivation

00:08:50.250 --> 00:08:53.560
is counterintuitive.
We have this notion that human beings are

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:57.500
these purely mechanistic creatures -- that,
if you simply push the levers the right way

00:08:57.500 --> 00:09:00.630
at the right time, people will do what you
expect them to do.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:04.160
And that ain't true.
We're a lot more complicated than that.

00:09:04.160 --> 00:09:06.830
Let me give you some experiments, because
experiments are totally cool.

00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:15.560
I mean, I don't want to, it's warm in here.
I don't want to empty the room by reciting

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:18.941
all 40 years of research.
But some of these studies are totally interesting

00:09:18.941 --> 00:09:20.760
and cool.
My clicker is in my pocket.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:23.120
That sounds like -- "My clicker is in my pocket"
 -- that sounds like a euphemism, doesn't

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:24.120
it? [laughter]
[pause] My clicker is in my hand -- which

