also sounds like a euphemism. [laughter]
Where was I? Oh, yes.

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:45.100
We're talking about the science. Okay. It's
cool.

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:49.950
Let me tell you about some experiments, because
these experiments are really, really interesting.

00:09:49.950 --> 00:09:54.490
And they're really, really surprising.
So, let me tell you about one experiment that

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:58.380
comes from the mean streets of Cambridge,
Massachusetts. All right?

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:02.560
At the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
MIT.

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:05.460
Very interesting piece of research done by
some economists there.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:10.320
Some economists at MIT in collaboration with
some -- an economist at Carnegie Mellon and

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:14.200
at the University of Chicago.
So really -- not only the mainstream of the

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:17.670
economic profession -- but in some ways sort
of the 'elite' mainstream of the economics

00:10:17.670 --> 00:10:19.780
profession.
They did this really interesting study.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:24.470
They gave these MIT students a series of challenges
 -- a series of games and other kinds of tasks

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:28.230
to play.
Some physical tasks -- "Can you throw a ball

00:10:28.230 --> 00:10:31.840
through a hoop?"
Memorizing strings of digits, solving complex

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:37.190
conceptual puzzles -- a whole set of challenges.
And they said, "We're going to incentivize

00:10:37.190 --> 00:10:39.460
you.
We're going to incentivize you and reward

00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:43.280
you based on your performance.
So if you do reasonably well, you get this

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:49.870
small monetary reward.
If you do medium well, you get a medium monetary

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:52.100
reward.
But if you do really well -- if you're one

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:57.640
of the top performers -- you get a sizable
monetary reward." Okay?

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:00.780
The classic kind of motivational scheme.
Now, what happened?

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:05.530
Let's go to the videotape. Or -- it's not
videotape -- but let's go to this.

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:12.100
As long as the task involved only mechanical
skill, bonuses worked as they would be expected:

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:18.960
The higher the pay, the better the performance.
Nothing surprising about that, right?

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:25.020
Here's where the surprise comes.
But once the task called for even rudimentary

00:11:25.020 --> 00:11:29.440
cognitive skill.
Look at that phrase again -- "rudimentary

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:35.000
cognitive skill" -- and in an incredibly innovative
act of right-brain thinking, I made it red.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:42.080
In a rudimentary cognitive skill, a larger
reward led to poorer performance.

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:46.490
Now, that's kind of weird isn't it?
That's not the way it's supposed to work.

00:11:46.490 --> 00:11:48.180
You know -- if you want more of something,
reward it.

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:51.420
But that's not happened here.
So they say, "This is weird.

00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:53.890
What's going on here?"
So they test the assumption.

00:11:53.890 --> 00:11:57.610
Maybe giving 50 bucks to a student in MIT
isn't sufficiently motivating.

00:11:57.610 --> 00:12:00.240
So let's take the same experiment and do it
somewhere else.

00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:05.230
Let's do it in Madurai, India -- rural India,
where the standard of living is far lower,

00:12:05.230 --> 00:12:09.200
so a reward that's modest by American standards
is going to be more impactful.

00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:13.130
Same deal -- small rewards, medium rewards,
large rewards.

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:15.860
Same set of tasks.
Here's what happened this time.

00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:21.030
People offered the medium reward did no better
than people offered the small reward.

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:29.350
But this time around, people offered the largest
reward -- they did worst of all.

00:12:29.350 --> 00:12:34.200
Here we go. In eight of the nine tasks we
examined across three experiments, higher

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:41.070
incentives led to worse performance.
This is strange. This is not what I learned

00:12:41.070 --> 00:12:44.570
when I studied economics.
This is not the way it's supposed to work.

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:48.780
This seems to defy some of the laws of behavioral
physics.

00:12:48.780 --> 00:12:54.040
This seems -- in its own way -- vaguely leftist
and socialist to me.

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:59.110
It sort of undercuts certain tenets of capitalism.
Okay?

00:12:59.110 --> 00:13:02.480
But who spots -- first of all, these are done
by economists.

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:08.000
Let's look at the socialist organization that
sponsored the research -- Federal Reserve

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.600
Bank.
So this is the mainstream of the mainstream.

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:16.030
Top flight economists sponsored by the Federal
Reserve saying, "Higher incentives can lead

00:13:16.030 --> 00:13:18.860
to worse performance."
Here's what's interesting about this.

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:22.260
We think that if you reward something that
you want, you get more of it.

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:25.630
And that is not always the case.
And particularly for creative, conceptual

00:13:25.630 --> 00:13:31.220
tasks, that is actually rarely the case.
If you offer an "if-then" incentive for a

00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:36.880
kind of conceptually-challenging complex task,
people routinely perform worse.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:41.090
This is actually so clear that it's hardly
even controversial in the world of behavioral

00:13:41.090 --> 00:13:42.680
science.
It's hardly even controversial.

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:46.170
We see it over and over and over again.
So let's talk about -- that's "rewards" -- let's

00:13:46.170 --> 00:13:49.660
talk about "punishments".
Because punishment is actually a very powerful

00:13:49.660 --> 00:13:52.240
motivator as well.
And punishment is much more predictable.

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:57.340
So let's go from the mean streets of Cambridge
to the country of Israel.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:14:01.160
And let's talk about some day care centers
in Israel who had a problem.

00:14:01.160 --> 00:14:04.990
Day care centers in Israel -- the chain of
day care centers -- they noticed that some

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:07.880
parents were coming up late to pick up your
kids -- their kids.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:10.610
You had to come and pick up your kid by 4
p.m.

00:14:10.610 --> 00:14:15.250
Some parents were coming late.
So how do you disincentivize people from showing

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:18.760
up late?
What would you do?

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:23.990
Charge them! Exactly. You charge them.
You impose a fine; you impose a penalty.

00:14:23.990 --> 00:14:27.350
Absolutely right. Common place practice.
So that's what they do.

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:30.160
They say, "You know what? People are showing
up late.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:35.030
That's wrong. We're going to stop this behavior.
If you punish something, you get less of it."

00:14:35.030 --> 00:14:39.410
So they put up this sign, "Announcement: Fine
for Coming Late.

00:14:39.410 --> 00:14:42.020
