00:17:34.249 --> 00:17:37.850
their children.
So, they had a social obligation -- social

00:17:37.850 --> 00:17:41.919
convention.
I would even -- I would see your "social,"

00:17:41.919 --> 00:17:45.929
and raise it -- "moral." That is, they have
a moral obligation in some ways.

00:17:45.929 --> 00:17:50.529
They have a relationship, and that encouraged
them to -- that's why they actually -- most

00:17:50.529 --> 00:17:54.509
people actually -- complied with the rule.
But when you -- what it did is, it shifted

00:17:54.509 --> 00:18:00.309
this out of the social realm into the market
realm and it became nothing more than buying

00:18:00.309 --> 00:18:03.309
 -- it became similar to buying the bag of
Cheetos I got for John, all right?

00:18:03.309 --> 00:18:07.100
"Hey, I want three bags of Cheetos."
Open up your wallet; buy three bags of Cheetos.

00:18:07.100 --> 00:18:10.690
And so, human beings are not that mechanistic.
We do things for other reasons.

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:16.100
We do things because they're good and because
we care about other people and because we

00:18:16.100 --> 00:18:19.650
want to maintain that relationship.
So when you look at the science, it actually

00:18:19.650 --> 00:18:22.570
calls into question a lot of what we think
about human beings.

00:18:22.570 --> 00:18:25.390
And so, here's the gist of it.
Let's talk about -- we're going to talk about

00:18:25.390 --> 00:18:30.370
how this applies to work, but let me just
give you, in some ways, the "thumbnail sketch"

00:18:30.370 --> 00:18:37.740
here.
If you want people to do work that is routine,

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:42.029
that is rule-based -- I can use this word
here -- you want people to do work that is

00:18:42.029 --> 00:18:47.639
"algorithmic," okay?
Where you are -- this is the only place on

00:18:47.639 --> 00:18:53.309
the planet where you can say the word "algorithmic,"
and a third of the audience smiles in response

00:18:53.309 --> 00:18:54.309
to that one word.
[audience laughter]

00:18:54.309 --> 00:18:59.130
It's almost this Pavlovian nerd instinct [audience
laughter].

00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:07.690
"Algorithmic" -- woe! If the work is "algorithmic"
 -- that is, there's a set of rules, a process

00:19:07.690 --> 00:19:13.591
that you follow, a clear set of steps that
leads to a single conclusion -- the carrot

00:19:13.591 --> 00:19:16.899
and stick motivators are excellent for that
kind of work.

00:19:16.899 --> 00:19:20.889
They're really good.
For work that's not especially interesting,

00:19:20.889 --> 00:19:25.649
carrot and stick motivators are pretty good.
One of the dangers of carrot and stick motivators

00:19:25.649 --> 00:19:29.670
is that they can sometimes dampen or even
extinguish people's intrinsic motivation for

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:32.470
a task.
But if there's no intrinsic motivation to

00:19:32.470 --> 00:19:34.820
extinguish, then, you're not taking a big
risk.

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:38.391
So for tasks that are simple, tasks that aren't
especially interesting, tasks where you want

00:19:38.391 --> 00:19:43.149
a short-term result -- carrot and stick motivators
are awesome if you want short-term results.

00:19:43.149 --> 00:19:45.250
Awesome.
You get the Martins of the world leaping out

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:50.370
of their seat for ten bucks, instantly.
Uninteresting -- not particularly interesting,

00:19:50.370 --> 00:19:52.879
not especially complicated, short-term -- they're
awesome.

00:19:52.879 --> 00:19:57.870
But here's the thing -- how much of the work
that you do at Google is "not especially interesting,"

00:19:57.870 --> 00:20:01.960
"not especially complicated," and "only has
short-term results?"

00:20:01.960 --> 00:20:06.490
Maybe some portion of it, but the vast majority
of what you do is actually reasonably interesting.

00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:09.669
It's actually quite sophisticated and complicated
and conceptual.

00:20:09.669 --> 00:20:13.480
And you actually want the results to endure
for a long time.

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:18.869
And for those kind of work -- these contingent
"if-then" motivators simply don't work.

00:20:18.869 --> 00:20:23.820
There's 40 years of science that says this.
And the danger is -- or at least from my perspective

00:20:23.820 --> 00:20:27.059
 -- is that the science hasn't migrated to
the business world.

00:20:27.059 --> 00:20:30.740
That many people -- I think this company is
an exception -- many aspects of the business

00:20:30.740 --> 00:20:35.820
world, many institutions in the business world,
are basically operating on notions of human

00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:39.389
motivation that is rooted in folklore, not
in science.

00:20:39.389 --> 00:20:43.110
But I think if you listen to science, you
can run your companies in a fundamentally

00:20:43.110 --> 00:20:45.590
different way.
And there's some cool examples of how to do

00:20:45.590 --> 00:20:49.179
it differently.
So, let's talk about how to do this.

00:20:49.179 --> 00:20:54.409
Number one -- money is a motivator.
Money is a motivator. We saw it with Martin.

00:20:54.409 --> 00:20:58.100
Money is a motivator.
But money is the motivator in slightly different

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:01.590
way than we think.
The gist of it basically is that, for money

00:21:01.590 --> 00:21:06.950
to be a motivator, you got to pay people enough.
If people aren't being treated fairly, if

00:21:06.950 --> 00:21:10.610
people feel like they're being compensated
inadequately, if they feel like someone in

00:21:10.610 --> 00:21:14.720
the adjoining office, the adjoining cube,
is doing similar work, or isn't as good -- is

00:21:14.720 --> 00:21:17.610
getting paid more than them, you don't have
motivation.

00:21:17.610 --> 00:21:22.369
That is a motivation sinkhole.
If people can't support their family, this

00:21:22.369 --> 00:21:28.999
notion of a "third drive," is nonsense. Okay?
But once you pay people enough -- in fact,

00:21:28.999 --> 00:21:33.779
once you pay people a little bit more than
enough -- what you do as a motivator is, you

00:21:33.779 --> 00:21:38.570
take the issue of money off the table so people
can focus on their work.

00:21:38.570 --> 00:21:43.429
That is the best use of money as a motivator
 -- to take the issue of money off the table.

00:21:43.429 --> 00:21:48.450
Now, after the fact, profit sharing, even
stock options -- those are less corrosive.

00:21:48.450 --> 00:21:53.399
It's very difficult for any single one of
you to game -- to basically -- I hope it's

00:21:53.399 --> 00:21:59.309
very difficult for any of you to single-handedly
game the Google stock price.

00:21:59.309 --> 00:22:02.520
I hope that's true.
You might be smarter than I give you credit

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:06.789
for, but I hope that's true.
So after the fact, it's not so bad. But contingencies

00:22:06.789 --> 00:22:09.830
are bad.
Pay people enough so that they don't think

00:22:09.830 --> 00:22:12.559
about money, they think about work.
What else can you do?

00:22:12.559 --> 00:22:16.039
Well, there are three components that science
shows us that really lead to effective, enduring

00:22:16.039 --> 00:22:18.789
motivation, especially for complicated, conceptual
tasks.

00:22:18.789 --> 00:22:26.330
They are: Autonomy, Mastery, and Purpose.
Autonomy, Mastery, and Purpose.

00:22:26.330 --> 00:22:30.799
Autonomy, Mastery, and Purpose.
Let's start with "autonomy," which is in some

00:22:30.799 --> 00:22:38.919
ways the first among equals.
We want to be self-directed. You want to direct

00:22:38.919 --> 00:22:40.520
your own lives.
That is human nature.

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:44.259
There's a notion out there -- in companies
not like this one -- that if human beings

00:22:44.259 --> 00:22:50.211
were left alone without the threat of a punishment,
without the dangling of a carrot, people would

00:22:50.211 --> 00:22:55.850
do nothing.
This sort of the "lump" view of human nature.

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:58.870
I'm serious -- Oh, there are plenty of people
who believe this.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:02.010
Plenty of people who believe that if people
were not threatened with a punishment or enticed

00:23:02.010 --> 00:23:06.590
with a reward, they would just sit there and
do nothing.

00:23:06.590 --> 00:23:10.759
Now, what's curious about this is that no
one ever believes this about him or herself.

00:23:10.759 --> 00:23:14.519
They only believe it about other people. And
I think it's wrong.

00:23:14.519 --> 00:23:20.009
I think that is not human nature -- that human
nature is to be active and engaged.

00:23:20.009 --> 00:23:25.399
That is -- let's use a computer metaphor here
 -- I think that being active and engaged

00:23:25.399 --> 00:23:28.210
and curious?
That is our default setting.

00:23:28.210 --> 00:23:34.970
That is our default setting, okay?
When the product ships, when the box ships,

00:23:34.970 --> 00:23:37.470
that's the default setting -- to be active
and engaged.

00:23:37.470 --> 00:23:42.529
And any of you have kids or have seen kids
 -- I have yet to see a 2-year-old who's not

00:23:42.529 --> 00:23:45.679
active and engaged.
I have yet to see a 4-year-old who's not active

00:23:45.679 --> 00:23:49.880
and engaged.
It is manifest as day that that is our natural

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:53.909
state -- that that is our default setting.
Now, I've seen plenty of 14-year-olds and

00:23:53.909 --> 00:23:57.889
34-year-olds and 44-year-olds who are not
active and engaged -- who are passive and

00:23:57.889 --> 00:24:00.429
inert.
But looking at that doesn't mean that's their

00:24:00.429 --> 00:24:03.989
natural state.
What it means is that the default got changed

00:24:03.989 --> 00:24:07.649
through a whole set of experience.
But if we awaken that default, I think great

00:24:07.649 --> 00:24:10.200
things can happen.
And I think you guys have done actually -- in

00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:13.600
many ways -- a masterful job of that.
Truly, masterful job of that.

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:16.889
And I've said that in venues other than this
one. [audience laughter]

00:24:16.889 --> 00:24:21.999
Just for credibility's sake.
