00:30:45.239 --> 00:30:50.330
I'll give you $2,000."
Isn't that? I don't even know what to call

00:30:50.330 --> 00:30:51.619
that.
You know what I mean?

00:30:51.619 --> 00:30:54.600
I mean, I -- seriously, I don't know how to
describe -- it's like a negative carrot or

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:59.090
something like that.
And then, they go and they take their jobs

00:30:59.090 --> 00:31:08.899
as call center representatives and here are
their instructions: "Serve the customer. Solve

00:31:08.899 --> 00:31:17.239
the customer's problem."
That's it. "Do it the way you want. If it

00:31:17.239 --> 00:31:20.359
takes you one minute, great.
If it takes you one hour, no problem."

00:31:20.359 --> 00:31:22.869
Now, of course, they get feedback from customers
to make sure that they're being treated well.

00:31:22.869 --> 00:31:25.720
What happens?
Zappos comes out of nowhere to be one of the

00:31:25.720 --> 00:31:29.729
highest customer-service-ranked companies
in any industry in this country -- higher

00:31:29.729 --> 00:31:33.799
than the Four Seasons.
Okay? Taking this job that we think is inherently

00:31:33.799 --> 00:31:40.940
deadening, infusing it with some autonomy,
boom! People perform, because we're not innately

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:43.289
passive and inert.
Let's talk about mastery.

00:31:43.289 --> 00:31:46.440
Mastery is a second urge.
Mastery is our desire to get better at something,

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:49.690
particularly better at something that matters.
It is a fundamental human impulse.

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:54.759
It is so powerful that people do things that
seem economically irrational. Okay?

00:31:54.759 --> 00:31:58.369
Let's talk about economic irrationality, and
let's talk about open source.

00:31:58.369 --> 00:32:05.039
Now, open source in economic terms is very
weird, okay? And we forget that.

00:32:05.039 --> 00:32:07.229
We're so kind of anchored in the present,
we forget that.

00:32:07.229 --> 00:32:13.239
So if you go back say 15 years or 20 years
and if you described open source as a business

00:32:13.239 --> 00:32:18.609
model to anybody -- particularly an economist
or a business school professor -- they would

00:32:18.609 --> 00:32:22.509
think that you were high.
I mean, I just ima -- can you -- I mean, imagine

00:32:22.509 --> 00:32:26.479
 -- "Oh, I got this great business model."
If it's 1995, "Hey, I've got this great business

00:32:26.479 --> 00:32:29.179
model.
Here's what it is: People will work to create

00:32:29.179 --> 00:32:32.330
software."
Okay, 1995 -- the year of Window's '95, right?

00:32:32.330 --> 00:32:36.809
And those of you who remember.
You remember when Windows '95 came out.

00:32:36.809 --> 00:32:40.899
It was like huge news, okay?
"But you know, I think there's another model

00:32:40.899 --> 00:32:45.330
out there, and here's how it would work.
You got these people -- these really technically-skilled

00:32:45.330 --> 00:32:47.859
people who fetch decent wages in the labor
market.

00:32:47.859 --> 00:32:51.239
And what they do is, they volunteer their
labor.

00:32:51.239 --> 00:32:55.090
They work really hard for free.
And then, wait -- it gets better.

00:32:55.090 --> 00:33:01.779
Then, they give away their product.
You with me? This is going to be awesome."

00:33:01.779 --> 00:33:06.950
I don't think you could -- I mean, you could
go down to Menlo Park or any venture capital

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:10.420
firm, or any economist or anybody who thought
they knew anything about business, they would

00:33:10.420 --> 00:33:15.539
say, "Uh, it doesn't quite work that way.
That seems actually vaguely delusional to

00:33:15.539 --> 00:33:19.299
think that it could."
You look at something like -- what's curious

00:33:19.299 --> 00:33:23.200
about this is that, they're wrong.
It does work -- Linux.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:28.600
It does work -- Apache.
It does work -- reasonably well -- Wikipedia.

00:33:28.600 --> 00:33:34.320
Wikipedia. You realize that Microsoft who
created Encyclopedia, vaguely around the same

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:39.460
time as Wikipedia, had all the right incentives
 -- all the things that economists at business

00:33:39.460 --> 00:33:43.220
school professors would tell you to do.
Encarta is out of business.

00:33:43.220 --> 00:33:44.919
Wikipedia is the biggest encyclopedia in the
world.

00:33:44.919 --> 00:33:50.029
That seems to have sort of almost sort of
biologically impossible 15 years ago.

00:33:50.029 --> 00:33:53.309
And yet, that's what it is.
So what's going on? Why are people doing this?

00:33:53.309 --> 00:33:56.509
Think about motivation.
Think about mastery and open source from the

00:33:56.509 --> 00:34:00.009
employer's perspective.
Here you have technically-sophisticated people

00:34:00.009 --> 00:34:05.239
doing demanding work for decent wages.
But their urge for something is so deep that

00:34:05.239 --> 00:34:10.530
they spend their discretionary time doing
equally -- if not more -- challenging work

00:34:10.530 --> 00:34:15.429
for someone else for free.
Think about being the employer.

00:34:15.429 --> 00:34:19.929
You say, "What am I missing?
What am I not providing?" That economist asks,

00:34:19.929 --> 00:34:22.720
because this is a very curious puzzle.
They asked the question, and here's what they

00:34:22.720 --> 00:34:27.919
find out: The biggest motivator is enjoyment-based,
intrinsic motivation -- how creative people

00:34:27.919 --> 00:34:30.399
feel while working on the project. That's
what it is.

00:34:30.399 --> 00:34:32.589
People are looking for challenges.
They're looking to get better.

00:34:32.589 --> 00:34:35.349
They're looking for mastery.
They're looking for engagement.

00:34:35.349 --> 00:34:39.399
You see this over and over and over.
Another example.

00:34:39.399 --> 00:34:45.429
Just to go to even -- this is percolating
to the mainstream in a place like Harvard

00:34:45.429 --> 00:34:48.330
Business Review.
Harvard Business Review has a story in the

00:34:48.330 --> 00:34:51.409
January issue -- good piece of research -- about
what motivates people at work.

00:34:51.409 --> 00:34:57.070
Long, multiyear study of what motivates people
at work where people kept very extensive time

00:34:57.070 --> 00:35:02.010
diaries over several years to report how they
were feeling, to report their subjective well-being.

00:35:02.010 --> 00:35:05.910
Over the years, they find this -- there's
one motivator above all.

00:35:05.910 --> 00:35:08.900
One motivator stands out well above anything
else.

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:14.049
And here's what it is: Making progress in
one's work.

00:35:14.049 --> 00:35:17.910
Making progress -- that was the biggest motivator
for people.

00:35:17.910 --> 00:35:21.920
Making progress.
And the really good managers out there are

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:26.059
managers who recognize this.
Who recognize progress.

00:35:26.059 --> 00:35:31.030
Who say, "Wow, yesterday you were here, today
you're here."

00:35:31.030 --> 00:35:33.670
Who help people who honor that. Who respect
that.

00:35:33.670 --> 00:35:38.010
Who help people move toward that. Making progress.
What about incentives?

00:35:38.010 --> 00:35:41.250
Here's what the Harvard researchers say.
The key to motivation doesn't depend on elaborate

00:35:41.250 --> 00:35:46.339
incentive systems.
In fact, the people in our study rarely mentioned

00:35:46.339 --> 00:35:50.750
incentives.
Making progress is the biggest motivator.

00:35:50.750 --> 00:35:54.690
Finally, last but not -- oh, let's skip that
 -- last but not least.

00:35:54.690 --> 00:35:58.650
Last but not least -- Purpose.
Purpose. We want to be part of a cause larger

00:35:58.650 --> 00:36:02.270
than ourselves.
That's part of what it is to be human.

00:36:02.270 --> 00:36:07.030
We perform at a higher level sometimes when
we're animated by some kind of bigger purpose.

00:36:07.030 --> 00:36:10.950
We perform at a higher level when we feel
like our contributions to teammates actually

00:36:10.950 --> 00:36:13.420
creates something bigger than we could create
ourselves.

00:36:13.420 --> 00:36:17.700
Very, very powerful motivator.
And "purpose" -- I think more broadly -- is

00:36:17.700 --> 00:36:21.440
becoming an enormous animator of effective
business today.

00:36:21.440 --> 00:36:25.349
And you see that here.
You know, your mission what -- is "to organize

00:36:25.349 --> 00:36:28.950
the world's information," right?
So that people can -- what's the rest of it?

00:36:28.950 --> 00:36:36.940
Say again? So it's universally available.
Organize the world's information so it's universally

00:36:36.940 --> 00:36:39.780
available and -- useful.
Okay.

00:36:39.780 --> 00:36:42.750
This looks like it's sort of a surprise to
some of you, which is alarming.

00:36:42.750 --> 00:36:45.450
[audience laughter] But trust me. Check your
website.

00:36:45.450 --> 00:36:51.161
That's a big, transcendent purpose.
That's not -- that's not -- think about that

00:36:51.161 --> 00:36:54.930
purpose.
That is not profit maximization.

00:36:54.930 --> 00:37:01.710
That's not a purpose.
That is not even the light and engaged customers.

00:37:01.710 --> 00:37:04.340
It is at a higher order of magnitude than
that.

00:37:04.340 --> 00:37:07.520
It is about some kind of transcendent purpose.
And what you see here more and more among

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:10.590
effective businesses is that, we have the
profit motive.

00:37:10.590 --> 00:37:13.990
The profit motive is a good thing.
The profit motive is actually a really good

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:16.369
thing.
The profit motive is one reason why we have

00:37:16.369 --> 00:37:19.869
such a high standard of living.
I think the profit motive is good.

00:37:19.869 --> 00:37:25.440
It's not universally, permanently, you know,
unequivocally good, but I think the profit

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:29.730
motive is good -- good in the sense of effective
and actually good in the sense of moral in

00:37:29.730 --> 00:37:34.079
its own way.
But, the profit motive is not the only thing.

00:37:34.079 --> 00:37:39.450
And what's happening now more and more is
that, if you want really talented people to

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:43.420
come work at a place, you got to have a bigger
purpose, okay?

00:37:43.420 --> 00:37:47.670
Maximizing shareholder gain is not going to
get a lot of people up in the morning.

00:37:47.670 --> 00:37:50.390
It's not going to say, "Wow, I'm going to
do something really cool.

00:37:50.390 --> 00:37:56.950
I'm going to like --" If you have a mission
of maximizing shareholder gain, I don't think

00:37:56.950 --> 00:38:01.391
you would have that groovy thing that Ilana
just showed me Aned's globe, right?

00:38:01.391 --> 00:38:05.000
That's unbelievable, okay?
If you're animated by profit-seeking, you're

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:09.041
not going to get that kind of stuff.
You're not going to get the cool stuff.

00:38:09.041 --> 00:38:12.599
And so, what I think's going on right now
is that, the profit motive -- in order to

00:38:12.599 --> 00:38:16.270
be effective, but also to be good in a deeper
sense -- has to be anchored in some way to

00:38:16.270 --> 00:38:20.170
the purpose motive.
That when the profit motive becomes unmoored

00:38:20.170 --> 00:38:25.900
from the purpose motive, sometimes bad things
happen, but also, it's less effective.

00:38:25.900 --> 00:38:29.180
It's really less effective.
And I think that we see this in the high-performing

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:32.790
organizations today.
And I'll give just one quote from a venture

00:38:32.790 --> 00:38:35.760
capitalist -- an investor.
He says, "Today you have to have a purpose

00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:38.349
bigger than your product."
You have to have a purpose bigger than your

00:38:38.349 --> 00:38:39.849
product.
And I think that's a lot of what you're doing

00:38:39.849 --> 00:38:41.510
here.
I think it explains your success.

00:38:41.510 --> 00:38:45.000
So it's a delight to be with you, because
I think in many ways -- not in all ways -- but

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.890
in many ways, your purpose is bigger than
your product.

00:38:47.890 --> 00:38:51.430
In many ways, you have people in this place
who have the privilege of being able to move

00:38:51.430 --> 00:38:54.400
toward mastery.
And you actually have a more autonomous, self-directed

00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:57.329
environment than in most places.
And I think that's the recipe -- not only

00:38:57.329 --> 00:39:01.079
for a great company -- but I think it's a
recipe for a good company.

00:39:01.079 --> 00:39:12.280
And so, my hats off to you.
So let's take some questions. Yes.

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:13.560
&gt;&gt; [inaudible]

00:39:13.560 --> 00:39:29.670
Daniel Pink: Yeah. [pause]
Yeah, "How would you frame the behavior of

00:39:29.670 --> 00:39:33.770
the financial industry in response to these
things?" It is pretty clear.

00:39:33.770 --> 00:39:39.150
This goes back to the utterly shocking slide
that I put up there that money is a motivator.

00:39:39.150 --> 00:39:42.690
Okay?
If you give people -- one of the dangers of

00:39:42.690 --> 00:39:47.579
carrot and stick "if-then" rewards -- particularly
if they're short-term and high stakes -- is

00:39:47.579 --> 00:39:52.750
that some people, many people, will take any
route there, even if it means cheating.

00:39:52.750 --> 00:39:56.210
There's no question about that. And that's
some of what we saw.

00:39:56.210 --> 00:40:02.890
The other thing is that people become myopic
in the sense that they don't see the long-term

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:05.560
consequences of it.
And they don't care, even if it's against

00:40:05.560 --> 00:40:09.230
their own self-interest.
So you bundle up a package of securities based

00:40:09.230 --> 00:40:15.770
on essentially fraudulent -- not in the legal
sense -- dicey, let's say "dicey" mortgages,

00:40:15.770 --> 00:40:19.859
and then pass it off to somebody else.
Short-term, all is good.

00:40:19.859 --> 00:40:24.500
Long-term, you could be caught in the total
downdraft of this whole economy.

00:40:24.500 --> 00:40:28.930
So it forces us to be myopic, and it also
gets us to be very -- it narrows the breadth

00:40:28.930 --> 00:40:32.400
of our thinking as well.
So you actually become in some ways less creative.

00:40:32.400 --> 00:40:37.799
So I think that, in many ways, the financial
crisis -- an element of it -- shows you what

00:40:37.799 --> 00:40:42.039
happens when it's all carrot and stick -- or
it's all "carrot" -- and when people have

00:40:42.039 --> 00:40:44.660
 -- and especially short-term.
And the short-term thing is actually really

00:40:44.660 --> 00:40:50.750
important, because if the payoff is only short-term,
people will respond to that.

00:40:50.750 --> 00:40:53.660
There's pretty little question about that.
Now, let's go more broadly.

00:40:53.660 --> 00:40:57.119
Let's talk about executive compensation here
for a moment, because I think it's a slightly

00:40:57.119 --> 00:41:01.940
 -- it's a sort of connected issue.
The thing about executive compensation that

00:41:01.940 --> 00:41:06.619
I think actually does verge on fraudulent
 -- and not in the legal sense, but in the

00:41:06.619 --> 00:41:11.390
sort of a moral sense -- is that a lot of
executive compensation isn't even an "if-then"

00:41:11.390 --> 00:41:13.069
incentive.
Here's what it is.

00:41:13.069 --> 00:41:17.450
If you're an executive -- a high-level executive
 -- and your company does well, you get a

00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:21.401
huge amount of money.
If you're an executive and you run your company

00:41:21.401 --> 00:41:24.520
into the ground, you get a huge amount of
money.

00:41:24.520 --> 00:41:28.440
So it's not even like an incentive as much
as it is an entitlement in that regard.

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:32.930
Now, there's also this talk out there that
you hear in the financial industry -- "Hey,

00:41:32.930 --> 00:41:39.490
if we didn't pay these outlandish salaries,
these people wouldn't work here."

00:41:39.490 --> 00:41:43.230
Right? You've heard that. Okay?
I actually think that's a very interesting

00:41:43.230 --> 00:41:49.020
research question.
Let's try it, okay? [audience laughter] I'm

00:41:49.020 --> 00:41:51.279
serious. Let's try it.
Let's see what it is empirically.

00:41:51.279 --> 00:41:55.339
You're making a -- it's an interesting hypothesis.
Let's test it empirically.

00:41:55.339 --> 00:41:59.230
I actually think that you'd get a lot of talented
people going to jobs that pay a half million

00:41:59.230 --> 00:42:03.730
dollars a year even if two years ago they
paid $3 million a year.

00:42:03.730 --> 00:42:10.690
So I think there's a lot of -- you know -- it's
somewhat irritating because of the -- it's

00:42:10.690 --> 00:42:15.240
more than somewhat irritating -- it's extremely
irritating because of those kinds of factors.

00:42:15.240 --> 00:42:16.240
Yes, sir.

00:42:16.240 --> 00:42:17.640
&gt;&gt; [inaudible]

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:30.630
Daniel Pink: Yeah. Yeah.
If you force caps on CEO pay, you take away

00:42:30.630 --> 00:42:33.250
that person's autonomy.
You mean, sort of government caps.

00:42:33.250 --> 00:42:37.150
Yeah, I think you're right about that, actually.
And I think that that is sort of imposing

00:42:37.150 --> 00:42:40.630
a solution to this from the top down is not
going to work.

00:42:40.630 --> 00:42:44.280
Because all -- it's sort of squeezing a balloon.
And so, what people are going to come up with

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:49.420
"work arounds" around.
You saw this in the early 1990s when they

00:42:49.420 --> 00:42:55.950
put a -- sort of a supertax on executive compensation
above the then-lofty figure of 1 million.

00:42:55.950 --> 00:43:01.109
And so, what happened is that everybody put
their regular compensation at 1 million and

00:43:01.109 --> 00:43:04.130
then found other ways to compensate people
that were even more lucrative.

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:09.400
So I don't think the solution is necessarily
to impose a law or regulation to stop that.

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:11.849
I think the solution is actually in the hands
of shareholders.

00:43:11.849 --> 00:43:15.750
I think the solution is in the hands of boards.
And you have very compliant boards.

00:43:15.750 --> 00:43:19.240
Google's the exception.
You have very compliant boards, and you have

00:43:19.240 --> 00:43:25.280
actually very passive shareholders.
And the shareholders are getting mistreated.

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:35.720
[pause]
Who's next? What are your questions? Yes.

00:43:35.720 --> 00:43:38.510
&gt;&gt; [inaudible]

00:43:38.510 --> 00:43:47.940
Daniel Pink: Well, we have all kinds of motivations.
I mean, fear is a great motivator.

00:43:47.940 --> 00:43:49.960
You know, and so these kinds of things.
I mean, I think there's an interesting thing

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:53.970
about what you see in open source is that
people say, "Well, what about reputation?

00:43:53.970 --> 00:43:58.710
What about a acclaim? Is that a motivator?"
And it is, in a way, but not quite in the

00:43:58.710 --> 00:44:01.720
pure way that we think.
Because if you think about reputation and

00:44:01.720 --> 00:44:07.440
acclaim, it is itself a form of feedback.
It gives you a sense of feedback, and feedback

00:44:07.440 --> 00:44:12.000
is necessary if you want to move toward mastery.
And so, what's curious -- I'll tell you about

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:16.430
one study about this, about sort of the importance
of feedback and reputation.

00:44:16.430 --> 00:44:20.190
It's an interesting study of artists.
So they went to -- they studied these artists

00:44:20.190 --> 00:44:24.859
in the 1960s who were at the Art Institute
School in Chicago, okay?

00:44:24.859 --> 00:44:29.240
They were preparing to be artists.
And they talked to these -- they interviewed

00:44:29.240 --> 00:44:32.079
these students -- and they found out -- they
did these qualitative interviews to find out

00:44:32.079 --> 00:44:35.001
what their motivation was.
And they noticed two groups of people.

00:44:35.001 --> 00:44:38.510
Basically, because they were curious, "Why
are people coming to art school?

00:44:38.510 --> 00:44:41.630
What do they want to get out of art school?
How does it fit into their path?"

00:44:41.630 --> 00:44:46.220
And so, they noticed that some people had
very much an extrinsic orientation. Okay?

00:44:46.220 --> 00:44:50.549
"I'm really good at art, and I can become
rich and famous doing art."

00:44:50.549 --> 00:44:54.220
That was one motivator for people.
"I want the acclaim. I think I'm really good

00:44:54.220 --> 00:44:57.059
at it.
I think I can make a decent living off of

00:44:57.059 --> 00:44:59.000
it."
There were other people who said -- had a

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:04.470
more intrinsic orientation.
"I want to paint. I love painting; it's cool.

00:45:04.470 --> 00:45:07.290
It's what I do." Okay?
Sometimes you talk to artists, and they don't

00:45:07.290 --> 00:45:10.100
even have an actual -- they can't even articulate
why they're -- it's like, "This is what I

00:45:10.100 --> 00:45:12.550
do." Okay?
So you had two different orientations here.

00:45:12.550 --> 00:45:16.609
Now, what's so interesting about this -- so
they use this data to figure out admission.

00:45:16.609 --> 00:45:19.221
"Okay, so we have two different kinds of mindsets
coming in here.

00:45:19.221 --> 00:45:24.410
Okay da da da da."
So this sits there for awhile.

00:45:24.410 --> 00:45:26.990
Somebody then realizes that there's this trove
of qualitative data -- 20 years later.

00:45:26.990 --> 00:45:33.270
"Wow, I wonder what happened to these folks?"
It's fascinating, right? Follow up. What happens?

00:45:33.270 --> 00:45:41.510
Well, it turned out that a decent number of
them actually had attained decent amounts

00:45:41.510 --> 00:45:46.579
of acclaim and had great reputations and actually
were making good livings as artists.

00:45:46.579 --> 00:45:50.799
And you know who they were?
The intrinsically-oriented ones.

00:45:50.799 --> 00:45:55.700
So there's this kind of zen-like thing going
on that if you "pursue it, you won't attain

00:45:55.700 --> 00:46:00.410
it."
[audience laughter] You know? Grasshopper.

00:46:00.410 --> 00:46:05.770
And that's so interesting.
So it's like, you know, that if you -- that

00:46:05.770 --> 00:46:10.530
the folks who are most committed to those
kinds of external rewards were the ones who

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:15.740
were least likely to get it.
Why? We can speculate why.

00:46:15.740 --> 00:46:21.870
Being an artist is really, really hard, okay?
Doing anything well is really, really hard.

00:46:21.870 --> 00:46:27.650
It takes a really long time.
And you're less likely to stick with it if

00:46:27.650 --> 00:46:31.490
you don't really love it.
And so, because they really loved it, it was

00:46:31.490 --> 00:46:36.170
"what I do," they got a lot better at it.
They were willing to stick through the -- The

00:46:36.170 --> 00:46:42.420
other folks who were more extrinsically motivated:
"You know? I'll go sell insurance" -- not

00:46:42.420 --> 00:46:44.940
that there's anything wrong with selling insurance.
What do you think? One more, then we'll wrap

00:46:44.940 --> 00:46:46.670
up.
Yes, sir.

00:46:46.670 --> 00:46:52.010
&gt;&gt; [inaudible]

00:46:52.010 --> 00:47:13.770
Daniel Pink: Okay. In themselves? Okay.
So let's take that one. So the question's

00:47:13.770 --> 00:47:17.970
a good question.
"How can someone sort of lower in the ranks

00:47:17.970 --> 00:47:21.540
foster this kind of sense of motivation in
him or herself?"

00:47:21.540 --> 00:47:23.830
Okay, I think people can do a lot more than
they think.

00:47:23.830 --> 00:47:30.530
So let me offer actually a tactical idea on
that, okay?

00:47:30.530 --> 00:47:33.450
Let's talk about performance reviews here
for a moment.

00:47:33.450 --> 00:47:40.579
You're laughing about performance reviews.
What's the point of a performance review?

00:47:40.579 --> 00:47:44.160
Ideally, to provide -- tell me your first
name? Court.

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:48.900
Court says ideally to provide feedback.
Ideally to provide feedback.

00:47:48.900 --> 00:47:53.549
Now, we all know that that is actually not
the best mechanism for providing feedback.

00:47:53.549 --> 00:47:57.240
What's wrong with it as a mechanism for providing
feedback?

00:47:57.240 --> 00:48:00.740
It's too late. Very good.
Your first name was -- Patsy.

00:48:00.740 --> 00:48:03.789
Patsy says it's too late.
What's another flaw in that?

00:48:03.789 --> 00:48:10.710
It's tied to the money. That's a good point.
What about the session itself?

00:48:10.710 --> 00:48:18.920
Most performance reviews sessions -- you know
this -- it's Kabuki Theater, okay?

00:48:18.920 --> 00:48:21.390
[audience laughter]
It's basically people playing certain kind

00:48:21.390 --> 00:48:25.950
of rehearsed roles, right?
It's not typically -- sometimes it is -- an

00:48:25.950 --> 00:48:29.170
open conversation.
It's Kabuki Theater.

00:48:29.170 --> 00:48:34.349
And so, it doesn't work very well.
As Patsy said, it's too late, and it's also

00:48:34.349 --> 00:48:36.299
too infrequent.
Think about an athlete.

00:48:36.299 --> 00:48:42.589
Athletes get feedback all the time. Serena
Williams doesn't have a biannual performance

00:48:42.589 --> 00:48:46.920
review, you know? [audience laughter]
I mean, you're laughing, but it's crazy to

00:48:46.920 --> 00:48:49.039
think about that, right?
How are you going to get better at tennis

00:48:49.039 --> 00:48:52.510
if you only get feedback twice a year, all
right?

00:48:52.510 --> 00:48:55.619
And so, I think there's a better way to do
this -- a better way to do performance reviews.

00:48:55.619 --> 00:48:59.210
And basically, is a much more autonomous way.
And I think it's very effective for people

00:48:59.210 --> 00:49:03.250
 -- that Court says -- who are not the folks
in positions of traditional power.

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:07.599
And it is basically to take performance reviews
back. Take them back.

00:49:07.599 --> 00:49:14.650
Do not outsource your performance review to
managers or bosses or people of formal authority.

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:18.240
Take it back. And here's how it would work.
Basically, a Do It Yourself performance review.

00:49:18.240 --> 00:49:25.000
At the beginning of a month, set out your
goals -- your learning goals, and your performance

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:28.020
goals, okay?
Set them out at the beginning of the month.

00:49:28.020 --> 00:49:34.099
And then, at the end of the month, call yourself
into the office. [audience laughter]

00:49:34.099 --> 00:49:40.660
Give yourself a stern, but loving, assessment
of how you're doing.

00:49:40.660 --> 00:49:43.410
Where are you making progress?
Where are you falling behind?

00:49:43.410 --> 00:49:47.130
The other question that we don't ask enough
in performance reviews is, "What tools or

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:50.750
information do you need to do things better?"
Okay?

00:49:50.750 --> 00:49:54.940
Ask yourself that. Ask yourself that question.
And that's how you can move toward greater

00:49:54.940 --> 00:49:57.190
and greater mastery on your own.
Take them back.

00:49:57.190 --> 00:50:00.590
The other thing that's very interesting that
goes toward aspect of Court's question is

00:50:00.590 --> 00:50:04.040
that -- what I've seen is that -- this is
happening in a really interesting, somewhat

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:08.130
self-organized way.
So that you see this -- sometimes people will

00:50:08.130 --> 00:50:10.240
say, "It's too weird to call myself into the
office.

00:50:10.240 --> 00:50:15.210
I'm not going to have this secret conversation
with myself.

00:50:15.210 --> 00:50:18.680
But I will have it with a peer.
Or I will have it with two peers or three

00:50:18.680 --> 00:50:22.089
peers or four peers."
And so, you see this less inside of organizations

00:50:22.089 --> 00:50:26.170
but more among people who are self-employed
or small entrepreneurs who will fashion these

00:50:26.170 --> 00:50:30.400
groups and meet monthly and say -- So, Court,
Patsy, and I meet.

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:33.010
And I say, at the beginning of the month,
I say, "Listen, Patsy and Court, here's what

00:50:33.010 --> 00:50:36.910
I'm hoping to do this next month".
"Okay, great. Maybe think about this, that,

00:50:36.910 --> 00:50:39.319
the other thing," they say to me.
They tell me what they're trying to do in

00:50:39.319 --> 00:50:41.359
the next month.
At the end of the month, we meet.

00:50:41.359 --> 00:50:44.190
We sit down informally. Have some coffee.
"Okay, how'd you do?"

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:49.900
"Well, I didn't quite make those sales calls."
"Why not, Court?" Hold you accountable a little

00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:50.900
bit.
Give you feedback.

00:50:50.900 --> 00:50:53.380
"Oh, that was a really" -- and so, people
are yearning for this.

00:50:53.380 --> 00:50:56.160
So they're taking these back in a self-organized
way.

00:50:56.160 --> 00:51:02.670
So I think that reclaiming performance reviews
is one thing that individual contributors

00:51:02.670 --> 00:51:07.579
can really do to get better at stuff.
And I don't think that most organizations

00:51:07.579 --> 00:51:12.230
are fully committed to helping everybody get
better at stuff.

00:51:12.230 --> 00:51:15.410
And on that note, thanks for having me.

00:51:15.410 --> 00:51:16.049
[Applause]

